–nach 1155":"1120.–nakon 1155.","1120–1155":"1120.–1155","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1125–1162":"1125.–1162","1130–1179":"1130.–1179","1130–Male":"1130.–preminuo","1080–1125":"1080–1125.","1080":"1080","1125":"1125.","1179":"1179","1155":"1155","1099":"1099","1120":"1120.","1130":"1130.","1162":"1162","nach 1155":"nakon 1155.","1160":"1160","about 1130":"oko 1130.","Zundert, Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Nizozemska","Holland, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Noord-Brabant, Nizozemska"},"cs":{"1120–nach 1155":"1120–po 1155","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1125–1162":"1125–1162","1130–1179":"1130–1179","1130–Male":"1130–Zesnulý","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1080":"1080","1125":"1125","1179":"1179","1155":"1155","1099":"1099","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","nach 1155":"po 1155","1160":"1160","about 1130":"okolo 1130","Zundert, Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Nizozemsko","Holland, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Noord-Brabant, Nizozemsko"},"da":{"1120–nach 1155":"1120–efter 1155","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1125–1162":"1125–1162","1130–1179":"1130–1179","1130–Male":"1130–Afdød","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1080":"1080","1125":"1125","1179":"1179","1155":"1155","1099":"1099","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","nach 1155":"efter 1155","1160":"1160","about 1130":"omkring 1130","Zundert, Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene","Holland, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene"},"nl":{"1120–nach 1155":"1120–na 1155","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1125–1162":"1125–1162","1130–1179":"1130–1179","1130–Male":"1130–Overleden","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1080":"1080","1125":"1125","1179":"1179","1155":"1155","1099":"1099","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","nach 1155":"na 1155","1160":"1160","about 1130":"circa 1130","Zundert, Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Nederland","Holland, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Noord-Brabant, Nederland"},"en":{"1120–nach 1155":"1120–after 1155","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1125–1162":"1125–1162","1130–1179":"1130–1179","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1080":"1080","1125":"1125","1179":"1179","1155":"1155","1099":"1099","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1162":"1162","nach 1155":"after 1155","1160":"1160","about 1130":"about 1130","Zundert, Zundert, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Zundert, North Brabant, Netherlands","Holland, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"North Brabant, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Breda","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Angelo, Dino, Domenic, Donato, Egidio, Geno, Massimo, Quintino, Sante, Ugo.","Italian: topographic name from medieval Latin <i>braida</i> ‘grassy meadow, flat grassland adjoining a settlement’, or a habitational name from any of the places called with this word, such as the districts (now suburbs) of Genoa, Milan, Mantua, and Brescia called Breda or Brera.","Dutch: habitational name fromthe city of this name in North Brabant."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gerard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]},{"name":"Hendrik","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Henrik ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]},{"name":"Reinier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Rayner</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gerard Hendrik Reinier van Breda van Brunesheim Schoten was born in 1120, in Zundert, North Brabant, Netherlands as the son of Engelbert van Breda. He married Béatrix de la Roche. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died after 1155."},"et":{"1120–nach 1155":"1120–pärast 1155","1120–1155":"1120–1155","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1